{
  "message": "fix(fcp-conformance): regenerate capability-token golden vectors (br-b6rtk)\n\nCommit 6df66c79 switched the canonical-CBOR encoder used by\nCwtClaims::to_cbor from numeric-i64 map-key ordering to RFC 8949\nbytewise lex (the correct spec-level canonical form). The three\ncapability-token golden vectors in vectors/capability.rs still held\nhex strings generated against the old ordering, so\n  * capability_golden_signature_single_byte_tamper_is_rejected\n  * all_vectors_verify (lib-level)\npanicked at baseline verification with \"non-canonical CBOR encoding\".\n\nRegenerated all three vectors by running a one-shot dump helper\n(regen_dump_golden_bytes, now kept as an #[ignore]d test for future\nregens) against the 0x01/0x02/0x03-seeded signing keys the existing\nvectors use. Both expected_claims_cbor and expected_token_cbor are\nrefreshed to match:\n\n  * claims CBOR: raw CwtClaims::to_cbor output, 8/11/8 entries for\n    vectors 1/2/3 (NO synthesized SCHEMA_VERSION \u2014 that's only added\n    during sign).\n  * token CBOR: payload after CoseToken::sign synthesizes\n    SCHEMA_VERSION=1 (so 9/12/9 entries, with the new Ed25519\n    signatures that follow).\n\nAdded an inline comment on vector 1 documenting why the two fields\ndiffer in entry count and pointing at the RFC 8949 ordering rule, so\nthe next regen doesn't have to rediscover it.\n\nVerified with\n  CARGO_TARGET_DIR=/tmp/fcp-review-A cargo test \\\n    -p fcp-conformance --lib vectors::capability\n  \u2192 31 passed.\n  CARGO_TARGET_DIR=/tmp/fcp-review-A cargo test \\\n    -p fcp-conformance --test negative_path_conformance\n  \u2192 6 passed.\n\nCloses br-b6rtk.\n\nCo-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.7 (1M context) <noreply@anthropic.com>",
